# Diffmap overhead bench, 2026-05-24

## Methodology

`examples/diffmap_overhead.rs` measures the wall-time delta between
`Cvvdp::score` (scalar JOD only) and `Cvvdp::score_with_diffmap`
(JOD + per-pixel diffmap, fills caller-owned `Vec<f32>`).

Per cell:

- 1 warmup call each direction (eats lazy-alloc + compile-cache costs)
- N=10 timed iterations per direction
- Median + p95 reported in microseconds

Backend: CUDA on RTX 5070, default features
(`--features cubecl-types`). Release build (`--release`).

## Results

| size  | scoring median (µs) | diffmap median (µs) | overhead |
|---    |---                  |---                  |---       |
| 256²  | 5359.78             | 5869.54             | +9.5%    |
| 512²  | 2943.83             | 3877.35             | +31.7%   |
| 1024² | 4332.67             | 5376.13             | +24.1%   |

The 256² timings show one-off allocator + compile-cache cost in
both directions (~5 ms each). The relative overhead at 256² is
the cleanest single number — the diffmap path costs about +0.5 ms
absolute on top of the ~5 ms scalar path.

512² and 1024² are closer to steady-state. The diffmap pass adds
~1 ms (512²) and ~1 ms (1024²) absolute, which scales sub-linearly
with pixel count — confirming the dominant cost is the channel-
pool kernel + readback (not the per-band bilinear upsample, which
would scale with pyramid depth, not base resolution).

## Acceptance gate verdict

The task spec said "if overhead > 30% wall, surface it; if > 50%,
that's worth a follow-on optimization chunk."

- 256² and 1024² are under the 30% surfacing threshold.
- **512² crossed the 30% threshold (+31.7%).** Likely a per-band
  alloc / handle-bump artifact that grew slightly with band count
  at intermediate sizes; the absolute wall delta (~1 ms) is small
  and well below the 50% follow-on-optimization threshold.

The diffmap kernel chain (3 zero kernels + N_LEVELS band-accumulate
launches + 1 channel-pool launch + 1 host readback of W·H f32)
shows up as the expected ~1 ms overhead. No surprise findings;
no follow-on opt chunk warranted from this measurement.

## Follow-on candidates (not blocking)

1. **Fuse the 3 zero kernels into one 3-channel launch** —
   currently we dispatch `diffmap_zero_kernel` 3× for the three
   base-res accumulators. A single `diffmap_zero_3ch_kernel`
   would halve the launch overhead. Expected wall save: ~30 µs
   per call (3 launches × ~10 µs each). Below the noise floor;
   nice-to-have.
2. **LDS-tile the channel-pool reduction** — analogous to the
   `pool_band_3ch_lds_kernel` win at large bands. The pool here
   is per-pixel (no reduction); LDS doesn't apply. Ignore.
3. **Skip the host readback when callers don't need the diffmap
   immediately** — out of scope (callers always consume the
   diffmap; the buttloop reducer is host-side).
4. **Lazy-alloc deferred to first diffmap call** — already done.

## Reproduction

```bash
cargo run --release -p cvvdp-gpu --features cubecl-types \
    --example diffmap_overhead -- --iters 10 --sizes 256,512,1024
```
